In a bid to create employment opportunities and by extension, see that the method used is replicated beyond Lagos State, the Lagos State Employment Trust Fund (LSETF), will be hosting 35 state governments, Non-governmental Organisations (NGOs), international agencies and corporate Organisation across Africa at the two-day employment summit in Lagos. The conference which is tagged: showcasing leading practices for job creation, will hold on the 5-6 of February, 2020 in Lagos, and is aimed at bringing together organisations that can create employment and governments who can influence policy that can help in creation of employment opportunities across the states and Africa. Speaking at the press conference is member board of trustees LSETF, Mr. Dele Martins, said in the last four years, “LSETF has gathered experience and learning which we can share with the other states. “Some of the pressures we are experiencing in Lagos in terms of migration is because there is not enough opportunities in other places and some of the strategies we have used successfully in Lagos is what we are planning to share with all participants from other states which hopefully, will lead to creation of job and employment within their respective states. “We intend to identify successful solutions in job creation, because at LSETF, the challenge of unemployment is not one we shy away from but rather embrace as our chore mandate and we are tackling it by devising entrepreneurships and employment opportunities, strategies, plans and intervention as it relates to creating and tackling of unemployment in Nigeria and Africa at large and by this summit, we would have saved them of the stress of reinventing the wheel.” Also speaking, the acting executive secretary, LSETF, Teju Abisoye, said, “We encourage people who are interested in youths employment to participate in this programme. Women, youths, public and private sector should take a deliberate steps in solving unemployment issues. “We have invited 35 state governments, NGOs, international agencies, corporate organisations across Africa and this not just people who are already doing other employment programmes but people who are also interested in learning about the structure of LSETF and use it in focusing on critical points of how states can address the issue of creating jobs, and future of work in their sectors.” 